<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>English Language and Literature</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/A5A7FB60-453A-48D2-9428-714D2A990E02"><gtr:id>A5A7FB60-453A-48D2-9428-714D2A990E02</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sebastiaan</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Henri Lucas Marie</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Aarts</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/38DB6BBE-318B-47B4-B0AF-184342C2550B"><gtr:id>38DB6BBE-318B-47B4-B0AF-184342C2550B</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sean</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Adrian</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Wallis</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>RESEARCHER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-000-23-1286"><gtr:id>3EB2BBA8-FB00-45ED-8C82-C87CE5B6C29B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Next generation tools for linguistic research in grammatical treebanks</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-000-23-1286</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research&amp;nbsp;will develop, in conjunction with an existing community of researchers, a software environment for carrying out experimental research in corpus linguistics. The outcome will be a computer program to assist linguists in carrying out scientific experiments on parsed corpora - databases of sentences of naturally occurring speech and writing for which a grammatical tree analysis has been produced.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Previous research has focused on developing grammatical query systems permitting linguists to retrieve instances of particular grammatical patterns. However, formal experiments require careful planning, are time consuming and prone to error.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The program will support an entire experimental cycle including:&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>defining the structure of an experiment and its variables &lt;/li>
 &lt;li>extracting a sample from the corpus &lt;/li>
 &lt;li>carrying out a statistical analysis on this sample, and &lt;/li>
 &lt;li>evaluating the results by considering the original sentences&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul> 
&lt;p>A range of techniques will be available to help researchers define and carry out experiments. The platform will be based on the user-friendly ICECUP&amp;nbsp;(International Corpus of English&amp;nbsp;Corpus Utility Program) software and new tools will be developed to help researchers focus their experiments, define new variables and interpret the results. Researchers can contrast explanations for the same event, while the software will try explanations unlikely to have been considered.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>155832</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput><gtr:description>ICECUP IV (the ICE Corpus Utility Program IV) is a brand new corpus experimentation system designed for parsed corpora such as ICE-GB and DCPSE. This new software can help linguists carry out complex experiments into the interaction of grammar and lexis with ease. Experiments that were previously difficult become simple, entire batteries of hypotheses can be considered together and the results can be evaluated against the corpus.</gtr:description><gtr:id>B05CBFD8-6964-4B95-B9FD-85BE2AF45AEC</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Improved technical capability for linguistic research has permitted novel research questions to be asked of linguistic data, such as psycholinguistic evidence into the way that lexical-grammatical decisions within sentences can be shown to interact in the course of their construction. The project focused primarily on the computational support for research and, to a lesser degree, incorporating statistical analysis. Since the project was completed the principal researcher has focused on developing statistical resources for linguists, publishing papers, tools and a blog.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>5452640c35a371.44336988</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:title>ICECUP IV</gtr:title><gtr:type>Software</gtr:type><gtr:url>http://www.ucl.ac.uk/english-usage/resources/icecup/iv.htm</gtr:url><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2007</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutput></gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A7020FD6-087D-4D1B-9382-11B590C2DF46</gtr:id><gtr:title>-squared: The Origin and Application of</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Quantitative Linguistics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/25bb7bdc3bdf6e8515d298fdb4aac229"><gtr:id>25bb7bdc3bdf6e8515d298fdb4aac229</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Wallis S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2013-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>54525fd59c1542.37301545</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>64AFFA40-AD34-4F0B-97B5-BCF01DC8B5F4</gtr:id><gtr:title>Annotation, retrieval and experimentation : or : you only get out what you put in</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Studies in variation, contact and change in English</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c5c8ebfe5d1bcfb4873e43b097daa2e6"><gtr:id>c5c8ebfe5d1bcfb4873e43b097daa2e6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sean Wallis (author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2007-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_129209587813631b1e</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>C9BC099F-D156-4B9C-90B9-CB33